<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-10-20T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-10-20T10:00:00-05:00" n="82" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d82">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">310.357/10–2050: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Norway</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Snow</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret   <gloss target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss>
                                    </hi>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Oslo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-10-20T16:00:00+01:00">October 20, 1950—4 p. m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>405. Reference <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 288, October
                                19. Saw Foreign Minister<note n="1" xml:id="d82fn1">H. M.
                                    Lange.</note> this noon. He said Norwegian <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> delegate had sought instructions and
                                he had replied directing vote against Indian proposal. He stated
                                these instructions unequivocal permitting delegation no alternatives
                                and that he was gratified learn that US was maintaining its stand
                                favor of Lie’s continuance in office. He asked whether I knew what
                                British position would be. I replied had no knowledge, but imagined
                                if prominent Commonwealth candidate put forward, might slightly
                                complicate British viewpoint. He said British <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> delegate told him very recently British not
                                interested seeing Indian as Secretary General.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Snow</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>